02:54:12,680 --> 02:54:38,280
A bitter wind blew the last leaves from the trees as Fox
made his way across the fields in search of food.

1885
02:54:38,280 --> 02:54:46,160
The lake had been frozen for weeks and the livestock were
tucked up safe and warm in the farmer's winter barns.

1886
02:54:46,200 --> 02:54:49,160
Fox couldn't remember when he had last eaten.

1887
02:54:49,160 --> 02:54:58,840
His skinny ribs stuck through his patchy, moth-eaten coat, his teeth chattered and the hard frosty ground hurt his paws
as he walked.

1888
02:54:58,880 --> 02:55:16,960
"Not a chicken, not a bird, not a puny little rabbit…not a scrap of food for a fox to eat…I shall surely die of cold
and hunger," he muttered miserably as he huddled up against a gnarled old tree trunk for shelter.

1889
02:55:17,000 --> 02:55:31,560
Earlier that morning, not far from where our Fox was crouching, Mrs Tom Cobbler was busy fussing around her
husband and shooing him out of the farmhouse.

1890
02:55:31,560 --> 02:55:55,480
"Here's yer shopping list Mr Tom Cobbler - one nice, juicy leg of pork, 2 kilos of potatoes, half a bag of carrots, 2
onions and some big, firm cooking apples for our Sunday lunch. Now don't you go forgetting anything Mr Tom Cobbler. You're the most forgetful man I ever knew!" and she waved a dishcloth at him.

1891
02:55:55,480 --> 02:56:07,160
"Yars, Mrs Tom Cobbler…er I mean… no dear, I won't forget." And he stuffed the shopping list in his trouser pocket and
walked off to market.

1892
02:56:07,160 --> 02:56:16,440
It was a long, cold walk to market and it was a long, hard walk back with his rucksack full of his wife's Sunday
shopping.

1893
02:56:16,440 --> 02:56:26,840
Mr Tom Cobbler decided to sit down for a moment's rest beside a tree. (The very tree our Mr Fox was going to huddle
close too later on.)

1894
02:56:26,840 --> 02:56:35,200
After his rest and before he set off down the lane he looked about for a place to hide his shopping bag and saw a hollow
in the tree trunk.

1895
02:56:35,240 --> 02:56:48,920
"Ah, that'll do, he said. "That'll keep it safe from foxes – that hole's far too small for a plump ol" fox to climb
through." And off he tramped up the hill towards the farmyard.

1896
02:56:48,920 --> 02:57:00,320
Well…what a nice surprise for our Mr Fox crouching beside
that very same tree later that morning.

1897
02:57:00,320 --> 02:57:08,400
His sly foxy nose began to twitch…and he sniffed the cold
wintry air…there was a whiff of FOOD nearby!

1898
02:57:08,400 --> 02:57:14,760
And it seemed to be coming from the hollow of the very tree
he sat against.

1899
02:57:14,800 --> 02:57:23,120
And because he was so very starved and thin – our TOO THIN
MR FOX was able to slip easily through into the hole.

1900
02:57:23,120 --> 02:57:25,640
And what did he find inside?

1901
02:57:25,640 --> 02:57:27,120
That's right!

1902
02:57:27,160 --> 02:57:29,600
All Mrs Tom Cobbler's Sunday dinner!

1903
02:57:29,600 --> 02:57:31,440
And what did he do with it?

1904
02:57:31,440 --> 02:57:32,720
That's right!

1905
02:57:32,720 --> 02:57:36,960
He gobbled it all up, lickity-quick.

1906
02:57:36,960 --> 02:57:49,600
And he felt very full indeed…SO full in fact that our TOO THIN FOX had become TOO FAT FOX in a matter of ten minutes
flat!

1907
02:57:49,800 --> 02:57:52,840
Too fat in fact to fit back through the hole.

1908
02:57:52,880 --> 02:58:06,640
So our Mr Fox had to wait and wait for days and days until his plump little tummy turned thin once more…and he could
climb back out through the hole of the tree again and off in search of food.

1909
02:58:06,640 --> 02:58:12,600
Which just goes to show – that if you wait long enough – the
problem might go away.

1910
02:58:12,600 --> 02:58:16,760
And what happened to old Mr Tom Cobbler that day?

1911
02:58:16,760 --> 02:58:26,440
Well, Mrs Tom Cobbler wasn't happy at all that he'd lost the Sunday roast - so he had turnip soup and potato peel pie
instead!

1912
02:58:26,440 --> 02:58:28,120
THE RAT AND THE ELEPHANT

1913
02:58:28,120 --> 02:58:39,880
A Rat was walking through the city.

1914
02:58:39,880 --> 02:58:51,320
He was a very proud Rat who believed that he was the most
frightening animal alive.

1915
02:58:51,360 --> 02:58:55,000
"Oh, yes!" said the Rat to himself.

1916
02:58:55,000 --> 02:58:57,360
"Everyone's scared of me."

1917
02:58:57,360 --> 02:59:01,960
"Scary Rat coming through. Out of my way."

1918
02:59:02,000 --> 02:59:08,080
The Rat turned a corner and saw a crowd of people standing
by the side of the road.

1919
02:59:08,080 --> 02:59:10,000
"Brilliant," thought the rat.

1920
02:59:10,000 --> 02:59:12,560
"I do like a crowd."

1921
02:59:12,560 --> 02:59:20,560
He jumped out into the middle of the road right in front of the crowd and waited for the first scream... but there
wasn't one.

1922
02:59:20,560 --> 02:59:23,560
Everybody was staring up the road.

1923
02:59:23,560 --> 02:59:26,400
Nobody even noticed the Rat.

1924
02:59:26,400 --> 02:59:29,960
"Look everybody," said the Rat.

1925
02:59:29,960 --> 02:59:32,720
"Over here. Rat. See."

1926
02:59:32,760 --> 02:59:34,160
Nothing happened.

1927
02:59:34,160 --> 02:59:38,640
The people were all too busy looking up the road.

1928
02:59:38,640 --> 02:59:41,520
"This is ridiculous," said the Rat.

1929
02:59:41,520 --> 02:59:45,240
"Are you all blind? Can't you see me?"

1930
02:59:45,240 --> 02:59:47,600
Then the Rat saw what the people were looking at.

1931
02:59:47,600 --> 02:59:52,120
An elephant was coming down the road.

1932
02:59:52,120 --> 02:59:58,760
Sitting on the elephant's back and stroking a large white
cat rode the King.

1933
02:59:58,920 --> 03:00:00,840
"Wow," said a man.

1934
03:00:00,840 --> 03:00:04,640
"Just look at the size of that elephant!"

1935
03:00:04,640 --> 03:00:08,600
"Never mind the elephant," said the Rat.

1936
03:00:08,600 --> 03:00:11,960
"What about me. Look at me. I'm a scary rat."

1937
03:00:11,960 --> 03:00:16,880
"Yes look at its wonderful long trunk," said a woman.

1938
03:00:16,920 --> 03:00:21,800
"That's just its nose," said the Rat.

1939
03:00:21,800 --> 03:00:23,160
"I've got a nose."

1940
03:00:23,160 --> 03:00:26,160
"And its huge ears," said a little girl.

1941
03:00:26,160 --> 03:00:31,760
"I've got ears," said the Rat, jumping up and down.

1942
03:00:31,840 --> 03:00:33,320
But nobody was listening.

1943
03:00:33,320 --> 03:00:37,680
They were too busy admiring the enormous elephant.

1944
03:00:37,680 --> 03:00:41,880
"That is the most wonderful creature in the whole world,"
they all said.

1945
03:00:41,880 --> 03:00:45,520
"No...no!" said the Rat.

1946
03:00:45,520 --> 03:01:09,480
"There's nothing wonderful about elephants. How many legs have they got? Four like me. How many eyes have they got?
Two like me. What colour are they? Grey like me. See, I'm exactly the same as an elephant except an elephant's really slow and boring and I'm truly the most fierce and terrifying creature in the world."

1947
03:01:09,520 --> 03:01:14,120
But nobody noticed the Rat... ...apart from the King's Cat.

1948
03:01:14,280 --> 03:01:22,640
"Look at me...look at me. I'm exactly like an elephant "cept
better.

1949
03:01:22,640 --> 03:01:24,120
Elephant's are rubbish.

1950
03:01:24,120 --> 03:01:26,400
I am the most fierce and..."

1951
03:01:26,400 --> 03:01:30,000
The Rat didn't finish what he was saying because...

1952
03:01:30,040 --> 03:01:36,720
...in an instant the white cat had run down the elephant's
trunk and was staring the Rat in the face.

1953
03:01:36,720 --> 03:01:44,600
"Exactly like an elephant, eh?" said the Cat looking down at
the Rat.

1954
03:01:44,640 --> 03:01:54,560
"Well maybe not exactly," said the Rat looking nervously at
the cat's sharp claws.

1955
03:01:54,600 --> 03:02:03,160
"Obviously my nose isn't quite as long...my ears are a bit
smaller...and I haven't got a king riding on my back…"

1956
03:02:03,160 --> 03:02:06,600
Suddenly the Cat's paw flashed out and pinned the Rat to the
ground.

1957
03:02:06,600 --> 03:02:08,320
The Rat couldn't move.

1958
03:02:08,360 --> 03:02:13,960
"Think I could do this to an elephant?" said the Cat.

1959
03:02:13,960 --> 03:02:17,480
"Um...not sure," said the Rat.

1960
03:02:17,480 --> 03:02:25,200
The Cat scooped up the Rat and held him up to her mouth.

1961
03:02:25,200 --> 03:02:29,600
"Think I could do this to an elephant?" said the Cat.

1962
03:02:29,640 --> 03:02:34,440
"No, maybe not," said the Rat shaking in fear.

1963
03:02:34,640 --> 03:02:42,240
"Think I could eat an elephant in two seconds flat?" asked
the Cat.

1964
03:02:42,240 --> 03:02:44,920
"Nope," whispered the Rat.

1965
03:02:44,920 --> 03:02:53,520
"Look what I've found," said the Cat to the people putting
the terrified Rat back down on the ground.

1966
03:02:53,520 --> 03:03:00,400
The Rat was shaking and looked so small and scared that
people weren't at all frightened of him.

1967
03:03:00,440 --> 03:03:02,600
"What is it?" said a man.

1968
03:03:02,600 --> 03:03:07,040
"Sort of mouse I think," said his wife.

1969
03:03:07,040 --> 03:03:09,240
"Funny little mouse thing probably."

1970
03:03:09,240 --> 03:03:26,120
As he slunk away the Rat heard the Cat say "A rat and an elephant may be the same colour but that doesn't make them
the same size. You remember that...Mr Rat."

1971
03:03:26,120 --> 03:03:30,800
And the Rat did remember that.

1972
03:03:30,800 --> 03:03:32,800
For ever.

1973
03:03:32,800 --> 03:03:36,480
THE ANT AND THE DOVE

1974
03:03:36,480 --> 03:03:52,000
It was another hot, dry day in the forest…

1975
03:03:52,040 --> 03:04:03,840
Ant had been wandering over crinkly, dry leaves for days in
search of a nice, cool drink…

1976
03:04:03,880 --> 03:04:14,880
"All I need is a drop of rain falling from a leaf – or a tiny pool of dew on a flower petal – or even a muddy
puddle…" he thought.

1977
03:04:14,880 --> 03:04:21,320
But it was so hot all the dew and puddles in the forest had
dried up.

1978
03:04:21,320 --> 03:04:26,960
"I'm so thirsty, that I have no choice," Ant sighed at last.

1979
03:04:26,960 --> 03:04:29,920
"I shall have to go in search of the Roaring River."

1980
03:04:30,960 --> 03:04:34,080
Ant had been warned about the Roaring River.

1981
03:04:34,120 --> 03:04:42,320
"It roars and it swirls and if you go too close, it will
sweep you away," a wise owl had told him.

1982
03:04:42,320 --> 03:04:44,360
But Ant was desperate.

1983
03:04:44,360 --> 03:04:50,960
"The river has more drops of water than all the rain clouds
in the world," he thought.

1984
03:04:50,960 --> 03:04:53,480
"It's my only hope of staying alive."

1985
03:04:53,480 --> 03:04:54,800
So Ant headed off.

1986
03:04:54,800 --> 03:05:02,360
He plodded on and on through the trees, until finally, he
heard rushing water ahead…

1987
03:05:02,360 --> 03:05:10,200
Before him lay the Roaring River – as vast as a sea, or so
it seemed to tiny Ant.

1988
03:05:10,200 --> 03:05:16,720
The fast flowing waters looked frightening – but Ant was too
thirsty to feel fear…

1989
03:05:16,720 --> 03:05:23,080
He clambered down the river bank and bent his weary head
into the water to drink it up.

1990
03:05:23,080 --> 03:05:31,160
The cool, sparkling water was so refreshing that Ant didn't
hear a roaring wave coming towards him…

1991
03:05:31,160 --> 03:05:41,200
Suddenly, he was flat on his back - his little legs in the
air, being swept away by the water!

1992
03:05:41,240 --> 03:05:43,400
"Help!" he cried.

1993
03:05:43,400 --> 03:05:45,800
"Someone save me, please!"

1994
03:05:45,840 --> 03:05:50,600
All of a sudden, a green leaf dropped onto the water by his
side with a plop.

1995
03:05:50,600 --> 03:05:55,160
"Quick, climb on!" cried a gentle cooing voice.

1996
03:05:55,160 --> 03:05:59,800
Ant didn't have time to see who the voice belonged to.

1997
03:05:59,840 --> 03:06:03,240
He just did what it told him…then he opened his eyes and
looked up.

1998
03:06:03,280 --> 03:06:09,080
Perching on the branch of a tree above was a pure white
Dove.

1999
03:06:09,120 --> 03:06:17,640
"Stay calm, little Ant - and wait for the gentle breeze to
blow the leaf to the river bank," she cooed.

2000
03:06:17,640 --> 03:06:19,320
Sure enough, the leaf carried Ant to safety.

2001
03:06:19,320 --> 03:06:25,400
He looked up – but the Dove had disappeared.

2002
03:06:25,400 --> 03:06:30,720
"I can't leave without thanking her," he thought.

2003
03:06:30,720 --> 03:06:33,840
"So I shall wait until she returns."

2004
03:06:33,840 --> 03:06:35,600
Ant waited and waited.

2005
03:06:35,600 --> 03:06:41,160
Then, just as he was about to fall asleep, he heard strange
noises.

2006
03:06:41,160 --> 03:06:43,440
They were coming closer and closer…

2007
03:06:43,440 --> 03:06:49,200
Two men emerged from the forest and stopped under the Dove's
tree.

2008
03:06:49,360 --> 03:06:54,040
One was carrying a bucket – the other a large, golden cage.

2009
03:06:54,040 --> 03:07:03,360
"This is the tree – the home of the most beautiful dove in
the land," said the man with the cage.

2010
03:07:03,360 --> 03:07:07,400
"I hope that glue in your bucket is sticky enough…"

2011
03:07:07,440 --> 03:07:13,800
"Indeed it is," said the second as he covered the branch
with a thick, green paste.

2012
03:07:13,800 --> 03:07:22,560
"When the Dove lands, its feet will stick to the branch – then we can put it in the cage and take it to the King. All
we have to do is hide and wait…"

2013
03:07:22,560 --> 03:07:23,960
Ant was horrified.

2014
03:07:23,960 --> 03:07:29,520
"I can't let this happen!" he thought.

2015
03:07:29,520 --> 03:07:35,040
"But what can a tiny creature like me do against two such
giants of men?"

2016
03:07:35,040 --> 03:07:38,320
Ant looked up as he heard the flapping of wings.

2017
03:07:38,320 --> 03:07:43,360
The Dove had returned and was about to land on the sticky
branch…!

2018
03:07:43,360 --> 03:07:48,480
"If I'm going to act, I must use the only weapon I have…"
thought Ant.

2019
03:07:48,520 --> 03:07:50,560
"And I must do it RIGHT NOW!"

2020
03:07:50,560 --> 03:07:57,400
So he jumped onto the men's feet – and bit as hard as he
could…time and time again…

2021
03:07:57,480 --> 03:08:03,280
"Yow!!!" they cried out in pain and took to their heels
through the forest.

2022
03:08:03,280 --> 03:08:10,760
"Thank you for saving me from a life in a cage," cooed the
Dove to Ant.

2023
03:08:10,760 --> 03:08:17,600
"And thank you for saving me from the giant wave," replied
Ant.

2024
03:08:17,600 --> 03:08:19,600
THE BOY WHO CRIED WOLF

2025
03:08:19,600 --> 03:08:31,160
A young boy got a job with a shepherd.

2026
03:08:31,160 --> 03:08:40,880
"Just keep your eyes open and look out for wolves" said the
shepherd.

2027
03:08:40,880 --> 03:08:48,720
"Wolves always try to eat my sheep. If you see one, ring
this bell and shout out "Wolf..!

2028
03:08:48,800 --> 03:08:50,200
Wolf..!"

2029
03:08:50,200 --> 03:08:53,320
Then we'll come running with our guns.

2030
03:08:53,320 --> 03:08:55,440
Can you do that, boy?"

2031
03:08:55,440 --> 03:08:58,000
"Don't you worry Mr Shepherd," said the boy.

2032
03:08:58,000 --> 03:09:00,800
"Your sheep are safe with me."

2033
03:09:00,800 --> 03:09:05,200
The boy took the sheep up into the hills and sat down with
his bell.

2034
03:09:05,200 --> 03:09:07,720
"Don't worry sheep," he said.

2035
03:09:07,720 --> 03:09:12,760
"I'm here now. I'm in charge. You'll be safe with me."

2036
03:09:12,760 --> 03:09:17,920
All morning the boy sat in the grass looking for wolves.

2037
03:09:17,920 --> 03:09:22,600
"I expect they're hiding," he said to the sheep.

2038
03:09:22,600 --> 03:09:25,720
That night the boy took the sheep back to the village.

2039
03:09:25,720 --> 03:09:31,400
The shepherd counted his sheep and was very pleased.

2040
03:09:31,480 --> 03:09:33,200
"Well done," he said.

2041
03:09:33,200 --> 03:09:36,480
"All safe. Same again tomorrow?"

2042
03:09:36,480 --> 03:09:39,800
"Yes sir!" said the boy.

2043
03:09:39,800 --> 03:09:42,680
The next day was exactly the same as the first day.

2044
03:09:42,720 --> 03:09:54,960
The boy took the sheep to the hills and sat down with his
bell looking for wolves.

2045
03:09:54,960 --> 03:09:56,200
There weren't any.

2046
03:09:56,240 --> 03:10:00,000
The boy noticed that the day felt very long.

2047
03:10:00,200 --> 03:10:12,520
There was no-one to talk to...except sheep...and the sheep
never talked back...they just ate grass...all day...

2048
03:10:12,560 --> 03:10:18,720
By the fifth day the boy was very bored with his job.

2049
03:10:18,720 --> 03:10:22,200
He looked up at the mountains.

2050
03:10:22,240 --> 03:10:24,040
Not a wolf in sight.

2051
03:10:24,040 --> 03:10:29,360
He looked down at the bell and he thought: "Maybe I could
just pretend there's a wolf."

2052
03:10:29,360 --> 03:10:42,480
So he picked up his bell... ...and rang it, shouting "Wolf...wolf... ...hurry...come quickly...there's a big old
wolf coming!"

2053
03:10:42,520 --> 03:10:45,120
Soon he could hear the sound of men running up the hill.

2054
03:10:45,120 --> 03:10:49,360
"Where is it?" said the shepherd.

2055
03:10:49,360 --> 03:10:52,400
"Gone," said the boy.

2056
03:10:52,560 --> 03:10:57,080
"He just ran off." "Well done boy," said the shepherd.

2057
03:10:57,080 --> 03:11:07,160
"You saved my sheep." The other men all patted the boy on the head and said how brave he'd been and what a good job
he'd done.

2058
03:11:07,200 --> 03:11:14,640
The boy felt so proud and pleased with himself that he
almost forgot that he'd made the whole thing up.

2059
03:11:14,640 --> 03:11:17,880
A few days later he was bored again.

2060
03:11:17,880 --> 03:11:25,720
"The only good day I had in this job was when I pretended
there was a wolf," he told the sheep.

2061
03:11:25,720 --> 03:11:31,800
"And I rang my bell and all the men came and told me what a
good job I'd done. It was brilliant."

2062
03:11:31,880 --> 03:11:33,080
He looked at his bell.

2063
03:11:33,080 --> 03:11:36,200
And that's when he decided to do it again.

2064
03:11:36,200 --> 03:11:42,520
He rang, he shouted and again the men came running.

2065
03:11:42,520 --> 03:11:45,280
"Where is it?" said the shepherd.

2066
03:11:45,320 --> 03:11:47,560
"Gone," said the boy.

2067
03:11:47,560 --> 03:11:53,720
"Ran away." This time the men didn't say "well done" and pat
him on the head.

2068
03:11:53,720 --> 03:11:57,360
This time they looked at the boy like they didn't believe
him.

2069
03:11:57,360 --> 03:11:59,560
"There was a wolf, honest," he said.

2070
03:11:59,560 --> 03:12:04,240
The men just walked back to the village without speaking.

2071
03:12:04,240 --> 03:12:07,680
Now the boy felt really sorry for himself.

2072
03:12:07,680 --> 03:12:12,200
"They know I rang my bell when there was no wolf."

2073
03:12:12,200 --> 03:12:23,840
Then out of the corner of his eye he saw a movement - a big grey thing was coming down the hillside heading straight for
the sheep.

2074
03:12:23,840 --> 03:12:26,640
The boy rang his bell and he shouted.

2075
03:12:26,680 --> 03:12:31,280
"Wolf...wolf...come quickly... ...there's a wolf!"

2076
03:12:31,280 --> 03:12:36,000
Down in the village the men heard the bell ring and just
carried on working.

2077
03:12:36,080 --> 03:12:39,240
"Little fool," said the Shepherd.

2078
03:12:39,240 --> 03:12:43,040
"Does he really think we'll fall for that again?"

2079
03:12:43,040 --> 03:12:45,000
The boy kept ringing his bell.

2080
03:12:45,000 --> 03:12:52,760
There were tears in his eyes as he watched the wolf make a
meal of one of the shepherd's fattest sheep.

2081
03:12:52,760 --> 03:13:00,400
"I rang my bell but nobody came," the boy told the shepherd
that evening.

2082
03:13:00,400 --> 03:13:15,880
The shepherd nodded "Nobody believes a liar...even when he's
speaking the truth."

